<dl id="n41095d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41095d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41095d"> 95(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">D</font> spots on her / gown, evil / thoughts <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n41095d"><li>FW 251.16f. </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/lexkf.htm#n41095d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/l39kf.htm#n41095d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n41095d">MS BL 47477-108</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:182 <a name="kfCCd3" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kfCCd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kf/kfd3.htm#n41095d">Draft: II.1&sect;6CC.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[<font size="-1">THINGS HEARD AND SEEN</font>]</font> In the <cite>Spiritual Diary</cite> <font color="green">[of E.S.]</font> &hellip; there is a charming picture of a place of training for maidens <font color="green">[in Heaven]</font>: &ldquo;&hellip; They receive their garments gratis, not knowing how, which they put on daily, having better ones for festivals. They also have little gardens; and so long as they are virgins, there are only flowers there, and not fruits until they become wives. When they see <mark>spots on their garments, it is a sign that they have had evil thoughts</mark>; and that they have done something wrong; these spots cannot be washed out &hellip;&rdquo; <small> George Trobridge, <a name="GTLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GTLS"><cite title="source">A Life of Emanuel Swedenborg</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (??) 199f [203]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
